@Node "Introduction" "RxCD Introduction"

  @{b}Introduction@{ub}


    This library contains low level functions to manipulate audio
    CD.

    A CD device is referred by a name, e.g. CD0 CD2, or by an
    unique CD descriptor ID returned by @{"CDCreate()" LINK "CDCreate"}.

    You may use CDCreate() for speed reasone if in your macro you
    use a lot of RxCD functions calls.

    You have to use CDCreate() anytime you want to add an
    interrupt.

    So the first argument of any CDXXX() function will always be
    a CD definition:

    - ID
      the ID returned by CDCreate()
    - CD
      a CD name or an ID
    - CDName
      a CD name, not an ID

    The second argument of most CDXXX() functions is an ARexx
    stem name. It is used to store debug informations.

    Quite all functions return an integer:
    - 0
      Success
    - >0
      Failure

    On failure, if you have supplied a valid second argument,
    there will be set the fields:

    - DevErr
      The exec.library device error

    - Status
      The SCSI2 Status

    - CC
      The Check Condition flag of Status. This is very important.

    - ASCIISense
      The sense data in ASCII format

    - Valid

    - ErrorCode
      Always 0x 70x 71x

    - SegmentNumber

    - FileMark

    - EOM

    - ILI

    - SenseKey
      The type of the error

    - Error
      The SenseKey in human form

    - Information

    - ASL

    - CSI

    - ASC
      With ASCQ you can know what happen

    - ASCQ

    - Reasone
      The ASC/ASCQ in human form

    - FRUC

    - SKSV

    - SKS

    See @{"sense" LINK "Sense"} format.

    Audio CD programming is not that easy. Different hardware
    devices and exec.library software devices may react in
    different modes. That means that your CD soft or hard device
    might refuse to perform some operation or they might perform
    that differently.

    Audio CD programming is very vendor specific.

    More info about SCSI2 standard may be found at
    http://www.uni-mainz.de/~tacke/scsi/SCSI2-index.html

@EndNode

